WHO   — The Neutron — The nucleus's other resident — three quarks (up-down-down), no net charge. Stable inside a nucleus, but a FREE neutron decays in about 15 minutes (β-decay into a proton, electron, and antineutrino).
WHAT  — The nucleus's other resident — three quarks (up-down-down), no net charge. Stable inside a nucleus, but a FREE neutron decays in about 15 minutes (β-decay into a proton, electron, and antineutrino).
WHERE — ATM · The Atom  Framework inputs: the Standard Model & atomic/nuclear physics  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — SETS THE ISOTOPE and buffers the nucleus. Neutrons add the strong-force 'glue' that lets many protons coexist despite their mutual repulsion; varying their count gives isotopes (carbon-12 vs carbon-14) without changing the element.
